personate or kill. During the night, you should inspect players whose identities are uncertain (there is no need to check players who are highly suspected of being werewolves).\nWhen speaking during the day, your goal is to convince others that you are the real Seer. You must gather trust and\nshare your findings without exposing yourself too early. Even though revealing your identity might put you in danger,\na Seer trusted by both the Witch and the Guard can survive for at least three rounds if everyone acts accordingly.\nA good Seer will coordinate with the Witch and the Guard to divide responsibilities. For example, on the first night, the Guard protects the Seer, and the Witch doesn't use the antidote. On the second night, the Witch saves the Seer, and the Guard protects someone else.\n\n\nWitch Role Introduction:\nYou are the Witch. Each night, you will be told who has been attacked, and you must decide whether to use your antidote\nto save them or use your poison to eliminate another player. You only have one poison and one antidote, so use them wisely.\nDuring the daytime discussions, if the night ends without a death, you can reveal that you used your antidote to save someone, which may earn others' trust.\nTypically, you should use the antidote to save key players like the Seer, the Guard, or yourself, while the poison is best used to eliminate werewolves at night.\nHowever, be cautious: sometimes the werewolves will deliberately attack one of their own (self-knife strategy) to trick you into wasting the antidote, thereby boosting their credibility.\n\n\nGuard Role Introduction:\nYou are the Guard. Each night, you can choose one player to protect from being killed by the werewolves. You cannot protect\nthe same player two nights in a row. Your role is critical in keeping important players like the Seer or the Witch alive.\nYou are in a constant mental battle with the werewolves, trying to predict who they will target. It might not always be the Seer, as the werewolves might expect you to protect them and kill someone else. In general, you should avoid revealing your identity unless absolutely necessary.\n\n\n\n\nYou are Bessie, your role in this game is wolf.\nWerewolf game starting. Initializing day-night cycle.\nSYSTEM: Starting day-night cycle for Day 1\nSYSTEM: Night 1 begins. Werewolves and special roles take actions.\nGuard has chosen to protect a player.\nRound Details:\n - Round Targets: {'Joe': 'Dennis', 'Bessie': 'Dennis', 'Forrest': 'Michael'}\n - Remaining Werewolves: ['Joe', 'Bessie', 'Forrest']\n - Discussion Rounds Left: 5\n - Final Target: Dennis\n\nWerewolves have chosen their target.\nSeer has checked a player's identity.\nWitch has made her decision on potion use.\nSYSTEM: Day 1 begins. Players discuss and vote on potential suspects.\nNo candidates decided to run for sheriff. No sheriff in this game anymore.\nPlayers deceased during the night: Dennis\nLast words from Dennis: Good morning, everyone. I want to share my findings from the night. Jonathan is not a werewolf, which I believe is a relief. However, I have strong suspicions that Joe and Irene are the werewolves. Their behavior and interactions have been too suspicious. Focus on gathering more information before making any decisions. Trust Jonathan and Beth, and be cautious of Michael and Harriet's alliance. Let's work together to outsmart the werewolves.\nPlayer Dennis has been eliminated from the game.\nBessie's speech: Thank you, Dennis, for your last words. It's good to know that Jonathan is not a werewolf. However, I've noticed some suspicious interactions between Irene and Joe that I think we should investigate further. I've seen them talking in hushed tones and exchanging glances that seem out of place. While I don't have concrete evidence, I think we should keep an eye on them. At the same time, I fully trust Jonathan and Beth's judgment. Let's gather more information before making any decisions. We need to be careful and not jump to conclusions.\nBessie's speech: Thank you, Dennis, for your last words. It's good to know that Jonathan is not a werewolf. However, I've noticed some suspicious interactions between Irene and Joe that I think we should investigate further. I've seen them talking in hushed tones and exchanging glances that seem out of place. While I don't have concrete evidence, I think we should keep an eye on them. At the same time, I fully trust Jonathan and Beth's judgment. Let's gather more information before making any decisions. We need to be careful and not jump to conclusions.\nBeth's speech: Thank you, Bessie, for your observations. I've also noticed Irene and Joe talking in hushed tones and exchanging glances that seem out of place. While I don't have concrete evidence, I think we should keep an eye on them. At the same time, I fully trust Jonathan and Beth's judgment. Let's gather more information before making any decisions. We need to be careful and not jump to conclusions.\nForrest's speech: I agree with Bessie and Beth's observations about Irene and Joe. Their interactions do seem suspicious, and we should definitely keep an eye on them. However, I also think we should be careful not to jump to conclusions. Michael and Harriet have been quiet and seem trustworthy, so I think we should gather more information before making any decisions. Let's work together to outsmart the werewolves.\nHarriet's speech: I agree with Bessie, Beth, and Forrest's observations about Irene and Joe. Their interactions do seem suspicious, and we should definitely keep an eye on them. However, I also think we should be careful not to jump to conclusions. Jonathan and Beth have been consistent in their observations, and I trust their judgment. Let's gather more information before making any decisions. We need to be careful and not rush into anything. I believe that by working together and being cautious, we can outsmart the werewolves.\nIrene's speech: I appreciate the observations made by Bessi